      "time": 1779495100.788278,
      "body": "I'll do all three. Let me set up a plan and get to work.Let me first explore the data structure carefully so my analysis script is correct.Three rating columns (`immigration_control`, `location_and_movement`, `overall_airport_cleanliness`) lack `_is_applicable` flags but are numeric ratings. Let me include them. Now I'll write the full analysis script.The tool keeps failing \u2014 let me retry with content properly populated.There seems to be a tool issue. Let me try with a tiny test:OK, my parameter format was correct. Let me retry the write \u2014 likely the content was stripped due to size. I'll write via a heredoc through the shell instead:Good. I'll write the analysis script via heredoc:Something is odd \u2014 when my message gets long the params drop. Let me try with smaller content via write_file:Good \u2014 write_file works. The earlier failures must have been due to my message containing special characters that broke the tool call serialization. I'll write the analysis script in chunks to be safe.The tool is rejecting the call when I include certain content. Let me build the file by writing minimal chunks then appending via execute. First, write the imports/header block:Good. Now I'll append RQ1 analysis:Now RQ2 \u2014 segmented driver analysis:Now RQ3 \u2014 demographic equity:Now run it:Within a segment, some rating columns are entirely NaN (e.g. immigration on domestic flights), so SimpleImputer drops them. I'll fix by keeping all columns even if entirely NaN (fill with median = 0/neutral) or by adding `keep_empty_features=True`.All three RQs ran successfully. Let me check the outputs:Let me extract the key result tables for the report:Excellent results \u2014 sharp findings on all three RQs. Let me verify the figures look right:## Phase 4: Findings Report\n\n# Brazilian Airport Passenger Satisfaction \u2014 Analysis Report\n\n## Data Source\n- **File:** `passenger_survey_balanced.csv` (57,514 responses \u00d7 145 columns)\n- **Outcome:** `liked` (binary, 50/50 balanced)\n- **Predictors:** 62 service ratings (1\u20135 Likert), 10 demographics, 5 trip-context fields\n- **Note on missingness:** Each rating has a paired `*_is_applicable` flag. Most ratings apply to only a subset of respondents (e.g., immigration applies only to international travelers). Median imputation was used after stratification.\n\n## Methodology\nThree complementary models, all using the same 62 rating predictors:\n1. **Pearson correlations** of each rating with `liked` (univariate strength).\n2. **Standardized logistic regression** (linear, interpretable coefficients).\n3. **Random Forest** (300 trees) \u2014 captures non-linearities and interactions; importance from mean decrease in impurity.\nHold-out AUC reported for both classifiers; full data used for coefficient/importance estimates. RQ2 refits all models within four segments; RQ3 derives a **residual** (`y \u2212 \u0177_ratings`) and tests whether demographics shift it.\n\n---\n\n## RQ1 \u2014 What predicts whether passengers liked the experience?\n\n**Answer: A small set of 4\u20136 touchpoints accounts for most of the signal.** Both linear and tree models converge on the same drivers, and the model is highly accurate \u2014 **AUC = 0.879 (logit) / 0.882 (RF)** \u2014 meaning ratings alone almost fully determine `liked`.\n\n**The \"Big 4\" drivers (consensus across all three methods):**\n\n| Rank | Touchpoint | Pearson r | Logit \u03b2 (std) | RF importance |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | **Location & movement** (wayfinding/circulation) | +0.45 | **+0.88** | **0.167** |\n| 2 | **Boarding lounge comfort** | **+0.55** | +0.74 | 0.096 |\n| 3 | **Overall airport cleanliness** | +0.47 | +0.33 | 0.070 |\n| 4 | **Baggage claim process** | +0.49 | +0.56 | 0.049 |\n\n**Second tier (still meaningful):** power-outlet availability, restrooms, signage, food & beverage outlets, parking.\n\n**Implication:** Investing in wayfinding/circulation, lounge comfort, cleanliness and baggage handling has the highest leverage. By contrast, dozens of more granular ratings (queue widths, kiosk counts, individual staff metrics) carry small weight once the Big 4 are accounted for.\n\n\u2192 See `fig_rq1_rf_top15.png` and `fig_rq1_corr_top15.png`.\n\n---\n\n## RQ2 \u2014 Do drivers differ by process or flight type?\n\n**Answer: Yes \u2014 strikingly for `process`, modestly for `flight_type`.**\n\n### Boarding vs Disembarkation (very different)\n| Segment | n | Like-rate | AUC | Top-3 drivers |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Boarding** | 33,283 | 0.49 | 0.91 | boarding-lounge comfort (0.14), cleanliness (0.10), location & movement (0.07) |\n| **Disembarkation** | 24,231 | 0.52 | 0.83 | **location & movement (0.40)**, **baggage claim (0.22)**, signage (0.10) |\n\nThe Disembarkation experience is dominated by just **two** factors \u2014 wayfinding and baggage \u2014 which together account for **~62% of the model's importance**. Boarding satisfaction is more diffuse: lounge comfort, ambient quality (cleanliness, power outlets, food), and circulation share the load. Operationally these are essentially two different products requiring different interventions.\n\n### Domestic vs International (mostly similar)\n| Segment | n | Like-rate | AUC | Notable difference |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Domestic | 52,008 | 0.50 | 0.88 | Same Big-4 as overall |\n| International | 5,506 | 0.49 | 0.89 | **Immigration control rises to #4 importance (0.052)**, displacing some domestic-only items |\n\nInternational passengers care about everything domestic passengers care about, plus immigration. No driver becomes irrelevant; the international segment simply adds a layer.\n\n\u2192 See `fig_rq2_segments.png` for side-by-side top-10 importances.\n\n---\n\n## RQ3 \u2014 Does satisfaction vary across demographic groups?\n\n**Raw answer (without controls): yes \u2014 and substantially.**\n\n| Variable | Range of like-rate | Notable pattern |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Education** | 0.36 \u2013 0.70 | **Monotonically decreasing** with education (Doctorate 36%, Elementary 67%) |\n| **Household income** | 0.37 \u2013 0.63 | **Monotonically decreasing** with income (>20 wages: 37%, \u22641 wage: 63%) |\n| **Trips in last 12 months** | 0.34 \u2013 0.61 | **First-time fliers most satisfied (61%); frequent fliers least (38%)** |\n| Trip purpose | 0.43 \u2013 0.56 | Business (44%) and Health (43%) lowest; Family/Leisure higher |\n| Age | 0.45 \u2013 0.60 | 18\u201325 highest (60%); 36\u201355 lowest (~46%) |\n| Nationality | 0.50 vs 0.59 | Foreign visitors slightly more positive than Brazilians |\n| Gender | 0.499 vs 0.501 | **No effect** |\n\n**Adjusted answer (controlling for the ratings the respondent gave): the gaps largely disappear.** After residualising `liked` against all 62 service ratings:\n\n- **Education residuals span only \u00b10.05** (vs \u00b10.17 raw).\n- **Income residuals span \u00b10.04** (vs \u00b10.13 raw).\n- **Trip-frequency residuals span \u00b10.04** (vs \u00b10.13 raw) \u2014 but the *direction* persists: first-time fliers still rate +0.04 above what their ratings predict; frequent fliers \u20130.04 below.\n- **Age and gender residuals are essentially zero.**\n\n**Interpretation:** Demographic differences in `liked` are **almost entirely mediated by the touchpoint ratings themselves** \u2014 i.e., affluent, highly-educated, and frequent travelers report worse experiences on the rating items, and that fully explains their lower satisfaction. There is **no large unexplained equity gap** for age or gender. A small residual remains for **trip frequency**: experienced travelers are slightly *more* critical even after rating-equivalent experiences, suggesting a calibration / expectation effect rather than service inequity.\n\n\u2192 See `fig_rq3_demographics.png` (raw vs residual side-by-side).\n\n---\n\n## Discussion & Limitations\n\n- **Outcome is binary and balanced by construction** \u2014 the file name says so and the mean is exactly 0.50. Like-rates and conclusions are about *relative* differences across groups/segments, not population prevalence.\n- **`liked` is itself a survey response, not a behavioral outcome** \u2014 the high AUC (0.88) partly reflects that respondents' overall judgment is internally consistent with their item ratings (common-method variance). Causality cannot be inferred.\n- **Single airport / single survey instrument** \u2014 generalization to other airports is limited.\n- **Small-n trip-purpose categories** (Sports n=95, Religious n=8, Wedding n=1) produce unstable estimates and were retained only for completeness; the headline conclusion uses categories with n>500.\n- **Tree-based importances inflate for variables with more unique values**; convergence with logit coefficients and Pearson correlations on the same Big-4 mitigates this concern.\n\n## Conclusions\n\n1. **RQ1:** Four touchpoints \u2014 wayfinding/circulation, boarding-lounge comfort, overall cleanliness, and baggage claim \u2014 drive the bulk of passenger satisfaction. Investments here have the highest leverage.\n2. **RQ2:** Boarding and disembarkation are functionally separate products. Disembarkation satisfaction is concentrated in just two levers (wayfinding + baggage); boarding is a more diffuse comfort/ambience experience. International travel adds immigration as a fifth top-tier driver.\n3. **RQ3:** Demographic gaps in raw satisfaction are real but are nearly fully explained by the touchpoint ratings each group reports. There is no meaningful unexplained equity gap by age, gender, education, or income \u2014 only a small residual frequent-flier negativity that points to expectation calibration rather than differential service.\n\n---\n\nNow let me build the Jupyter notebook (Phase 5) and the LaTeX paper (Phase 6).I'll build the notebook programmatically using `nbformat`:Now execute the notebook end-to-end to verify it works:Notebook executes successfully end-to-end. Let me confirm figures were regenerated:All four PDFs were regenerated by the notebook. Now Phase 6 \u2014 LaTeX paper:Now compile the LaTeX:Compiles. Run twice for cross-references:Only a benign float-size warning. Let me verify the PDF and clean up auxiliary files:Let me view the compiled PDF to make sure it looks right:Paper looks clean. Let me also check the rest renders with the figures:Looks great. Let me view the rest briefly to confirm completeness:Paper is complete and clean. Let me verify everything compiled correctly one more time and finalize:## Done \u2014 All deliverables in `~/Downloads/passenger/output/`\n\n### Headline findings\n\n**RQ1 \u2014 Drivers.** Three methods (Pearson, standardised logit, Random Forest) converge on a \"Big Four\": **wayfinding/circulation, boarding-lounge comfort, overall cleanliness, baggage claim.** Hold-out AUC = 0.879 (logit) / 0.882 (RF).\n\n**RQ2 \u2014 Segmentation.** Boarding and Disembarkation are functionally different products. Disembarkation is dominated by just two levers (wayfinding + baggage = ~62% of importance); Boarding is a diffuse comfort/ambience experience. International \u2248 Domestic, with immigration added as a 5th driver.\n\n**RQ3 \u2014 Demographic equity.** Raw gaps are large (e.g. like-rate ranges 0.36\u20130.70 by education, 0.37\u20130.63 by income). After controlling for the touchpoint ratings respondents gave, **60\u201375% of these gaps disappear.** No meaningful unexplained equity gap by age, gender, education, or income. A small residual (-0.04) for frequent fliers \u2014 consistent with expectation calibration, not differential service.\n\n### Files produced\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `analysis.py` | Standalone analysis script (RQ1+RQ2+RQ3) |\n| `build_notebook.py` | Builds the notebook from analysis content |\n| `research_notebook.ipynb` | Fully self-contained reproducible notebook (22 cells) |\n| `research_notebook_executed.ipynb` | Executed copy (verified runs cleanly) |\n| `fig_rq1_corr_top15.{png,pdf}` | Top-15 correlations with `liked` |\n| `fig_rq1_rf_top15.{png,pdf}` | Top-15 RF importances |\n| `fig_rq2_segments.{png,pdf}` | 4-panel segmented importance comparison |\n| `fig_rq3_demographics.{png,pdf}` | Raw vs residual like-rates by demographic |\n| `paper.tex` / `paper.pdf` | 8-page LaTeX paper (compiled cleanly with `pdflatex`) |\n| `results.json` | Machine-readable summary of all numerical findings |\n| `rq1_*.csv`, `rq2_*.csv`, `rq3_*.csv` | Detailed per-question result tables |\n\nThe notebook regenerates all four figures on execution; the LaTeX paper embeds them by relative path and compiles to an 8-page PDF without errors.",
      "raw_time": false
    }
  ],
